contents.name: HumanEnzyme
contents.description: Enzymes are proteins that act as biological catalysts by accelerating chemical reactions.

contents.name: Species
contents.description: In this project, we are focusing on the different effects of a virus infection on a host, specifically the effect of "SARS-CoV-2" virus on "Human" host.

contents.name: BindingToHostReceptorInteraction
contents.description: The ability of the virus to enter the host cells by binding its receptor-binding domain (RBD) in the Spike protein to a cell receptor called angiotensin-converting enzyme 2 (ACE2).?

contents.name: HumanProtease
contents.description: A protease is an enzyme that catalyzes proteolysis, breaking down proteins into smaller polypeptide through breaking the peptide bonds.

contents.name: MembraneFusionInteraction
contents.description:
Fusion between viral and cellular membranes forms a fusion pore through which viral RNA is released into the host cell cytoplasm for uncoating and replication.

Note that, the Host cell can be infected by many viruses -> multiple membrane fusion of the same cell.
While one virus can infect one cell -> one membrane fusion

contents.name: SARSCOV2ProteinCodingProcess
contents.description:
The "translation" process of viral genome into viral proteins. Note that, this process could not be happened without the recruiting of host proteins and apparatus.
(as an example we could add Human ribosome with NSP1)

contents.name: EntryEfficiency
contents.description: The efficiency of entry mechanisms of the virus into the host cell.

contents.name: Flexibility
contents.description: The property of proteins that confers them adaptability. Proteins are dynamic entities, and they possess an inherent flexibility that allows them to function through molecular interactions.

contents.name: Stability
contents.description: Stability is the potential of a pattern to survive over time, and therefore is integral to our understanding of biological systems and their evolution.?

contents.name: Functioning
contents.description: The general operation of a viral protein. Specific functions of mutated proteins (or of specific domains/portions of proteins) may be lost. As an example, a mutation may lead to lose an epitope region.

contents.name: StructuralOptimization
contents.description: The characteristic (optimal) 3-dimensional shape of a protein, including the secondary, super secondary (motifs), tertiary (domains) and quaternary structure of the peptide chain.?

contents.name: HostVirusInteraction
contents.description: The interaction between viral molecules and host molecule (To achieve or perform a process).

contents.name: ViralInfectionFormation
contents.description:
This Relator represents the viral infectivity, that is the capability of a transmitted virus to establish an infection. 
In order to establish the viral infection, the virus must enter the host cell and replicate inside it followed by spreading the virus from one cell into another inside the same host.

contents.name: ProteinProteinInteraction
contents.description: This category captures the different types of Protein Protein interaction, which is necessary during different steps of viral life cycle.

contents.name: ImmuneResponse
contents.description: The absence of immune response during an infection course means that the virus escaped the immune system -> immune escape

contents.name: ViralEntry
contents.description: The process of entering the virus itself (through endosomal entry) or entering its genome (through cell surface entry)

contents.name: ViralReplication
contents.description: The replication of the viral genome within the infected cells is a complex process involving the action of several viral and host proteins in order to perform RNA polymerization, proofreading and final capping.?

contents.name: ViralLoad
contents.description: The number of copies of RNA of a given virus per milliliter of blood.?

contents.name: Antibody
contents.description: Refers to the class of antibodies that is found and produced naturally (or after infection) in the human body.

contents.name: IncubationPeriod
contents.description: The incubation period is the interval between the moment a host is infected and the onset of the disease.

contents.name: ViralTransmission
contents.description:
The virus capability to pass from one host to another host?. 
Transmission could be between same species or cross-species

contents.name: InfectionDuration
contents.description: the time duration in which the host is infected with the virus

contents.name: ViralRelease
contents.description: Include the release of mature virus form infected host cell

contents.name: Vaccinated
contents.description: Human who has received a vaccine, no matter which kind or which dose

contents.name: Treatment
contents.description:
The act of drug administration to an infected person.
An infected person could receive multiple antiviral drug.

contents.name: TherapeuticAntibody
contents.description: Refers to the class of antibodies that is being handled in anyway in the laboratory and re-introduced to the patient as a type of therapy

contents.name: EffectivnessOfVaccine
contents.description: A measure of how well vaccines work in the real world.

contents.name: EffectivnessOfDrug
contents.description: A measure of how well antiviral drugs work in the real world.

contents.name: Diagnosis
contents.description:
The "diagnosis" differs from "DetectionProcess" in which the later is a specification of the former.

"Diagnosis" is the act of checking the presence of viral residue (generally) in a sample.
While "DetectionProcess" is the laboratory (or self done) process of checking the presence of viral residue (as viral proteins or immune system proteins) in a sample using at least one of the different diagnostics.

contents.name: Sample
contents.description: It is a sample taken from a human which is going under diagnosis process to decide if that human is infected or not.

contents.name: EffectivnessOfDiagnostics
contents.description: A measure of how well diagnostics methods work in the real world.

contents.name: DetectionProcess
contents.description:
The "diagnosis" differs from "DetectionProcess" in which the later is a specification of the former.

"Diagnosis" is the process of checking the presence of viral residue (generally) in a sample.
While "DetectionProcess" is the process of checking the presence of viral residue (as viral proteins or immune system proteins) in a sample using at least one of the different diagnostics.

contents.name: CtValue
contents.description: In a RT-PCR reaction, the CtValue is the number of cycles at which the fluorescence of the PCR product is detectable over and above the background signal.

contents.name: SensitivityToVaccinatedSera
contents.description: Responsiveness of the virus towards the sera of vaccinated plasma donors.

contents.name: SensitivityToConvalescentSera
contents.description: Responsiveness of the virus towards the sera of convalescent plasma donors.

contents.name: SensitivityToAntibodies
contents.description: Responsiveness of the virus towards antibodies (monoclonal, ployclonal, or recombinant)

contents.name: COVID19
contents.description: The respiratory disease that is being occurred as a result of SARS-cov-2 infection

contents.name: Disease
contents.description: Any disease that can affect a Human

contents.name: OtherDisease
contents.description: Any disease that could affect the human rather than COVID19

contents.name: Complications
contents.description: A concurrent disease, accident, or adverse reaction that aggravates the original disease. In our case it represents the complications between COVID-19 disease and other possible disease that the host has.

contents.name: FatalityRate
contents.description: The proportion of persons who die after the viral infection over the number of confirmed infected people

contents.name: Reinfection
contents.description: The risk of second infection by the same infectious agent, after recovery from -or during the course of- a primary infection.

contents.name: HospitalAdmission
contents.description:
The act of admitting to a hospital.
It is linked to "Human" rather than "Infected" because a person could be admitted to a hospital regardless of his/her infectivity status.

contents.name: ViralFitness
contents.description: The capacity of a virus to produce infectious progeny in a given environment.

contents.name: RiskOfHospitalization
contents.description: the risk of placing a patient in a hospital for diagnostic study and/or treatment

contents.name: BindingToAntibodies
contents.description: The ability of the virus to attack antibodies

contents.name: Interactions
contents.description:
It is a category that represents different types of interactions as being seen from two points of view:
1- From functional point of view: we have HostVirusInteraction and IntraViralProteinProteinInteractions. Both of them represent the interaction where a process was happened or function was made.
2- From PhysioChemical point of view: we have intramolecular (in the same molecule) or intermolecular (between two different molecules) interactions.

contents.name: IntraviralProteinProteinInteractions
contents.description: The function and activity of a protein are often modulated by other proteins with which it interacts.?

contents.name: IntermolecularInteraction
contents.description:
Are the forces that exist between molecules.
The forces holding molecules together. Intermolecular forces are particularly important in terms of how molecules interact and form biological organism.

contents.name: IntramolecularInteraction
contents.description: Are the forces that hold atoms together within a molecule.

contents.name: DiseaseSeverity
contents.description: An assessment of systematic symptoms caused by the virus.

contents.name: InfectedCellProtein
contents.description: The different proteins that are located inside the infected cell, those protein are involved in the viral genome translation process.

contents.name: ViralVirulence
contents.description: The competence of any infectious agent to produce pathologic effects
